1 covered multifamily dwellings and other types of dwellings in this state accessible to and
2 usable by all persons with disabilities, the Fair Housing Act.
3 SECTION 4. ORS 456.508 is amended to read:
4 456.508. As used in ORS 456.510 and 456.513:
5 (1) “Accessible” means that housing complies with federal accessibility guidelines implementing
6 the Fair Housing Amendments Act of 1988, 42 U.S.C. 3601 et seq., or the Uniform Federal Ac-
7 cessibility Standards, both as amended and in effect on [January 1, 2004] the effective date of
8 this 2026 Act.
9 (2) “Common living space” means a living room, family room, dining room or kitchen.
10 (3) “Contiguous units” means units that are on the same tax lot or on contiguous tax lots that
11 have a common boundary[.], including tax lots that are separated by a public road [are contiguous
12 tax lots for purposes of this subsection].
13 (4)(a) “New” means that the housing being constructed did not previously exist in residential
14 or nonresidential form.
15 (b) “New” does not include the acquisition, alteration, renovation or remodeling of an existing
16 structure.
17 (5) “Powder room” means a room containing at least a toilet and sink.
18 (6) “Rental housing” means a dwelling unit designed for nonowner occupancy under a tenancy
19 typically lasting six months or longer.
20 (7) “Subsidized development” means housing that receives one or more of the following devel-
21 opment subsidies from the Housing and Community Services Department:
22 (a) The federal low-income housing tax credit under 26 U.S.C. 42(a), if no part of the eligible
23 basis prior to the application of 26 U.S.C. 42(i)(2)(B) was financed with an obligation described in
24 26 U.S.C. 42(h)(4)(A), all as amended and in effect on [January 1, 2004] the effective date of this
25 2026 Act;
26 (b) An agriculture workforce housing tax credit, as described in ORS 315.164;
27 (c) A loan that qualifies the lending institution for a subsidized housing loan tax credit, as de-
28 scribed in ORS 317.097;
29 (d) Funding under the federal HOME Investment Partnerships Act, 42 U.S.C. 12721 to 12839, as
30 amended and in effect on [January 1, 2004] the effective date of this 2026 Act;
31 (e) Moneys from the Oregon Housing Fund created under ORS 458.620; or
32 (f) Moneys from other grant or tax incentive programs administered by the Housing and Com-
33 munity Services Department under ORS 456.559.
34 (8) “Visitable” means capable of being approached, entered and used by individuals with mobility
35 impairments, including but not limited to individuals using wheelchairs.
36 SECTION 5. ORS 456.510 is amended to read:
37 456.510. (1) Except as provided in this section and ORS 456.513, the Housing and Community
38 Services Department may not provide funding for the development of new rental housing that is a
39 subsidized development unless:
40 (a) Each dwelling unit of the housing meets the following requirements:
41 (A) At least one visitable exterior route leading to a dwelling unit entrance that is stepless and
42 has a minimum clearance of 32 inches.
43 (B) One or more visitable routes between the visitable dwelling unit entrance and a visitable
44 common living space.
45 (C) At least one visitable common living space.
[2]

SB 1576
1 (D) One or more visitable routes between the dwelling unit entrance and a powder room.
2 (E) A powder room doorway that is stepless and has a minimum clearance of 32 inches.
3 (F) A powder room with walls that are reinforced in a manner suitable for handrail installation.
4 (G) Light switches, electrical outlets and environmental controls that are at a reachable height.
5 (b) For a development that has a shared community room or that has 20 or more contiguous
6 units, there is at least one powder room available for all tenants and guests that is accessible.
7 (c) The subsidized development complies with the Uniform Federal Accessibility Stan-
8 dards, as amended and in effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act, except that a subsi-
9 dized development that falls within the multifamily housing occupancy classification, as
10 defined in the Uniform Federal Accessibility Standards, must provide features identified
11 within the standards that are appropriate for:
12 (A) Enabling, in a manner that is consistent with the Uniform Federal Accessibility
13 Standards, mobility for individuals who use wheelchairs or other mobility devices in the
14 greater of:
15 (i) The common areas of the subsidized development and at least 10 percent of the total
16 number of dwelling units in the subsidized development; or
17 (ii) The common areas of the subsidized development and at least two dwelling units, if
18 the subsidized development has 15 or more dwelling units; and
19 (B) Enabling, in a manner that is consistent with the Uniform Federal Accessibility
20 Standards, communication for individuals who are blind or deaf in the greater of:
21 (i) The common areas of the subsidized development and at least four percent of the total
22 number of dwelling units within the subsidized development; or
23 (ii) The common areas of the subsidized development and at least one dwelling unit, if
24 the subsidized development has 15 or more dwelling units.
25 (d) If the Uniform Federal Accessibility Standards apply to a dwelling unit, common area
26 or powder room within a subsidized development and are more stringent than standards that
27 apply to the unit, area or room under paragraphs (a) to (c) of this subsection, the subsidized
28 development must comply with the Uniform Federal Accessibility Standards.
29 (2) For a multistory structure without an elevator, this section applies only to dwelling units
30 on the ground floor of the structure.
31 (3) This section does not apply to agriculture workforce housing as defined in ORS 315.163 that
32 is located on a farm.
33 SECTION 6. (1) Section 2 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS 447.220, 456.508
34 and 456.510 by sections 3 to 5 of this 2026 Act become operative on January 1, 2027.
35 (2) The Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services and the Housing
36 and Community Services Department may adopt rules and take any other action before the
37 operative date specified in subsection (1) of this section that is necessary to enable the di-
38 rector and the department, on and after the operative date specified in subsection (1) of this
39 section, to undertake and exercise all of the duties, powers and functions conferred on the
40 director and the department by section 2 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS
41 447.220, 456.508 and 456.510 by sections 3 to 5 of this 2026 Act.
42 SECTION 7. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
43 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
